The code statements that lead to the bug are:
```java
if ("POST".equals(request.getMethod()) && request.getAttribute(WebUtils.ERROR_EXCEPTION_ATTRIBUTE) == null) {
    String paramValue = request.getParameter(this.methodParam);
```
Reason:
The `HiddenHttpMethodFilter` was allowing any HTTP method to be processed if the request method was "POST" and a parameter was present, without validating whether the method was one of the intended types (PUT, DELETE, PATCH). This lack of restriction could lead to unexpected behavior and security vulnerabilities.

The code statements that fix the bug are:
```java
String method = paramValue.toUpperCase(Locale.ENGLISH);
if (ALLOWED_METHODS.contains(method)) {
    requestToUse = new HttpMethodRequestWrapper(request, method);
}
```
Reason:
The patch introduces a check to ensure that only the allowed HTTP methods (PUT, DELETE, PATCH) are processed. By validating the `paramValue` against the `ALLOWED_METHODS` list before wrapping the request, it restricts the filter's functionality to the intended methods, thus preventing the potential for unexpected behavior and security issues.

